sentence:
The beat primarily reflects better-than-expected GI underwriting gains - mostly
from higher favorable PYD and lower catastrophe losses, better than expected buybacks,
somewhat offset by lower L&R earnings vs our estimates.

On an annualized basis, that would imply PIF
compression of 7.2% although we do not expect monthly trend to be constant over 12 months;
in fact, it should continue to decelerate by month.

It will be like an "x";
loss costs go down, then pricing goes up - where the two intersect in our view can take a bit
longer, especially given how long it is taking auto pricing to actually "earn" in.
